i believe what's going on is that most nihilists do not truly believe in the premise of ultimate pointlessness removing *all* purpose themselves.
it's more that it induces some amount of personal suffering proportional to how quickly your actions are guaranteed to vanish, and to cope with the suffering, they talk to others about it, perhaps also in hope that someone knows a solution to at least reasonably push back the point in time when your actions are guaranteed to vanish. i.e. the core point here is just that feeling like your actions matter and striving towards a greater goal is a basic human need that is inhibited to some degree by this issue. or in a single mantra: there is more to life than greater purpose, but greater purpose is certainly an important part of it, and without it, we feel somewhat lost.

one analogy i like is thinking of it as being stuck in a trash compactor with a bunch of other people.
if i have to live in the compactor for a couple of decades but it takes millions of years to crush all of us, i'm not terribly worried; everything i can ever aspire to accomplish will have perished by the time it all ends anyways.
if the compactor crushes us all within 100-150 years, i start struggling with the issue at hand: i may not experience it myself, but my children will, and all i have dedicated my life to is guaranteed to vanish within that time frame. this affects both my state of mind and my actions, and i may start talking to others about it in hopes of finding someone who can convince me that i'm wrong or that there is a way out.
